Problem Statemnet¶

The Aim is to find and prove the following :

Which variables are significant in predicting the reason for hospitalization for different regions

How well some variables like viral load, smoking, Severity Level describe the hospitalization charges

In [31]:
def find_outliers_IQR(df):

    q1=df.quantile(0.25)


    q3=df.quantile(0.75)

    IQR=q3-q1

    outliers = df[((df<(q1-1.5*IQR)) | (df>(q3+1.5*IQR)))]

    return outliers

Two sample ttest¶

  • Problem Statement : Prove (or disprove) that the hospitalization of people who do smoking is greater than those who don't Null and Alternative Hypothesis

  • Null Hypothesis ( $H_0):$ Average hospitalization charges of smoker and non-smoker are same .

  • Alternative Hypothesis ($H_a):$ Average hospitalization charges of smoker is grater than non-smokers .
  • $\mu_1$ - Average hospitalization charges of smoker
  • $\mu_2$- Average hospitalization charges of non-smoker

$H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2$

$H_a: \mu_1 > \mu_2$

In [263]:
from scipy import stats
stats,p_value=stats.ttest_ind(w1, w2,equal_var = False,alternative='greater')
print('The p-value is', p_value)
if p_value > 0.05:
     print('Since p_value > 0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
     print('Since p_value < 0.05 we reject the null hypothesis.')

The p-value is 6.739416029115544e-106
Since p_value < 0.05 we reject the null hypothesis.

Since p-value is less then 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis, which means that the average hospitalization charges for smokers is grater then average hospitalization charges of non-smokers¶
